The dfs function returns the height, and during the traversal, if the height reaches k-1, increments the answer and resets. So, translating the dfs function:

In Java:

private int dfs(int a, int pre) {
    int h = 0;
    for (int i : this.lists.get(a)) {
        h = Math.max(h, this.dfs(i, a));
    }
    if (0 < pre && h == this.k - 1) {
        h = 0;
        this.answer++;
    } else {
        h++;
    }
    return h;
} In Fortran, this would be a recursive function.

However, in Fortran, that requires reallocating and copying each time, which is a bit tedious. But in the Java code, during the construction of the Calculator:

for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    this.lists.add(new ArrayList<>());
} Then, for each i (0 to n-1), j = as.get(i).

is considered a problem and requires incrementing the answer. So in the input, if the first element (as.get(0)) is not 0 (but since in the code it's as.get(0) -1?), perhaps there's some confusion here. Wait, in the Java code, when reading the input:

as.add(sc.nextInt() -1);

So each input value is subtracted by 1. So the original input is 1-based, and converted to 0-based. So in the input, the first number (for node 0) is the parent (1-based), so subtract 1 to get 0-based.

For example, the first input number is the parent (1-based) of node 0, which is converted to 0-based by subtracting 1. So in Fortran, we'll read n integers, each as a(i) (1-based in the input?), then subtract 1 to get the 0-based parent index. Wait, the Java code's input processing:

n = sc.nextInt();
k = sc.nextInt();
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    as.add(sc.nextInt() - 1);
}

So the input is read as n numbers.

Wait, let's look at the Java code: In the Calculator constructor:

for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    int j = as.get(i);
    if (0 < i) {
        this.lists.get(j).add(i);
    } else if (0 < j) {
        this.answer++;
    }
} So when i is 0 (the first element in as), j is as.get(0).
